The UV-vis absorption spectrum of N-CDs (Fig. 2
                     a) showed a n-π* transition at 340 nm typical for N-CDs. The broad peak at 420 nm indicates the aromatic structure of N-CDs [5,8]. The PL spectra of the N-CDs were shown in Fig. 2b, with increasing of the excitation wavelength from 300 nm to 370 nm, N-CDs shows a blue emission peak which is centred at about 450 nm, the excitation wavelength of 380 nm shows a blue and green emission at the same time. Further increasing the excitation wavelength from 390 nm to 510 nm only exhibit the green emission peaks, which are centred at about 530 nm. All PL emissions of as-synthesized N-CDs by diverse mass ratios of FAC and urea were similar. Owing to the synergistic effect between rich hydrophilic groups on the surfaces of N-CDs, N-CDs could possess the unique emission properties [18]. The PL quantum yield (QY) of N-CDs was investigated (Table 1
                     ). The result indicates that the highest luminescent of N-CDs with blue fluorescence emission centred at 450 nm (λex = 360 nm) possesses a QY of 36.2% and green fluorescence emission centred at 530 nm (λex = 420 nm) has a QY of 47.6%. The QY of the N-CDs are higher than most of formerly reported CDs, especially for green N-CDs emitters (Table S1). By preparing a series of N-CDs, the nitrogen content (Table 1) of N-CDs change from 11.46% to 32.81% and then to 14.48%, corresponding to their emission efficacy, which illustrate that the doping of abundant nitrogen may lead to high QY. Fig. S3c reveals that all the fluorescence decay curves of N-CDs were optimum fitted to a single exponential function, and green luminescence reveals a longer fluorescence lifetime (τ) than blue luminescence (Table 1). The τ of all N-CDs being in the nanosecond regime indicates that the N-CDs are quite applicable to biological and optoelectronic applications [19].
